'''''Spring Ice''''' is a 1915–16 [[oil painting]] by Canadian painter [[Tom Thomson]]. The work was inspired by a sketch completed on [[Canoe Lake (Nipissing District)|Canoe Lake]] in [[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]]. The completed canvas is large, measuring 72.0 × 102.3 cm (28⅜ × 40¼ in). Painted over the winter of 1915–16, it was completed in Thomson's shack behind the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] in [[Toronto]]. The painting was produced as he was in the peak of his short art career and is considered one of his most notable works. While exhibited in a show put on by the [[Ontario Society of Artists]], the work received mixed to positive reviews. In 1916 it was purchased by the [[National Gallery of Canada]] in [[Ottawa]] and has remained in the collection ever since.

==Background==

[[File:Tom Thomson River.jpg|thumb|left|''River'', March–April 1915. National Gallery of Canada, Ottawa]]

{{Quote box|width=20em|align=right|quote="The ice is still on the lakes but it is getting pretty rotton {{sic}} and will break up the first good wind, so I will soon be camping again."|source=—Thomson in a letter to [[James MacCallum]], 22 April 1915{{sfnb|Thomson|1915}}{{sfnb|Murray|2002a|p=300}}}}

===1915 sketching season===
{{Further|Tom Thomson#Early recognition (1914–15)|Artistic development of Tom Thomson#Colour and experimentation (1914–15)}}

In the spring of 1915 Thomson returned to [[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]] earlier than he had in any previous year.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=132}} In a letter to [[James MacCallum]], he reported that he had already painted twenty-eight sketches by 22 April.{{sfnb|Thomson|1915}}{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=132}} He became fascinated with the "opening of the waters" as the ice on the lakes began to melt. This ice is apparent in the sketch ''River'', which was likely painted early in the season and preceding ''Spring Ice''. The close of the day is indicated by the turquoise, yellow and lavender sky.{{sfnb|Murray|2004|p=112}}

The year overall was particularly productive for Thomson, himself reporting that he had painted 128 sketches by September. He began to more consistently use hard wood-pulp board for sketching, something he picked up from [[J. E. H. MacDonald]].{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=132}} From April through July, he spent much of his time fishing, assisting groups on several different lakes. He spent much of his summer travelling across the province, hunting and sketching.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=131}} From the end of September to mid-October, Thomson spent his time at Mowat,{{sfnb|Little|1955|p=205}} a village on the north end of Canoe Lake.{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=102}} By November he was at Round Lake with Tom Wattie and Dr. Robert McComb.{{sfnb|Ghent|1949}}{{sfnb|Addison|Harwood|1969|p=46}} In late November Thomson returned to Toronto and moved into a shack behind the Studio Building that Harris and MacCallum fixed up for him,{{sfnb|Addison|Harwood|1969|p=84}}{{sfnb|Little|1970|p=179}} renting it for $1 a month ({{Inflation|CA|1|1915|fmt=eq|r=0|cursign=CAD$}}).{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=13}}{{efn|group=note|In his 1959 piece, "My Memories of Tom Thomson," [[Thoreau MacDonald]] (son of [[J. E. H. MacDonald]]) cited November 1915 as when Thomson moved into the shack behind the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]].{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=132n119}} Most sources agree with this, including Charles Hill,{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=132}} William Little{{sfnb|Little|1970|p=179}} and Addison & Harwood.{{sfnb|Addison|Harwood|1969|p=84}} David Silcox has written that the move happened in either late 1914{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=127}} or early 1915.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=127}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|pp=12–13}}}}

